---
import SeoLandingLayout from "../../components/SeoLandingLayout.astro";

const page = {
  title: "Makeup for Hooded Eyes: Techniques That Actually Show",
  description:
    "Learn makeup techniques specifically for hooded eyes. From the crease illusion to eyeliner placement, discover how to make your eyeshadow visible all day.",
  faq: [
    {
      q: "What are hooded eyes?",
      a: "Hooded eyes occur when a fold of skin droops over the crease, partially or fully covering the mobile eyelid. Unlike deep-set eyes (which sit further back in the socket), hooded eyes have extra skin that drapes over the lid from above. You can test this by looking straight into a mirror in natural light: if you can barely see your lid space above the lash line, you likely have hooded eyes. The hooding can range from a barely-there fold to a heavy brow bone that covers most of the eyelid.",
    },
    {
      q: "Why does my eyeshadow disappear on hooded eyes?",
      a: "The skin-on-skin contact created by the hood causes creasing and transfers pigment away from where you applied it. Regular eyeshadow placement assumes the crease is visible when your eyes are open, which is not the case with hooded lids. The shadow gets trapped in the fold and effectively disappears. Additionally, many primers are too thick for the thinner skin on hooded lids, accelerating the creasing process. The solution is working with a 'false crease' placement and using formulas designed for longevity rather than intensity alone.",
    },
    {
      q: "What is the best eyeliner for hooded eyes?",
      a: "For hooded eyes, a thin, tight-lined approach works best. Thick lines will be swallowed by the hood and transfer to the upper fold. Use a fine-tip gel or felt-tip liquid liner to create a subtle wing that extends slightly upward, giving the illusion of a lifted lid. Avoid lining the inner third of the upper lid, as this can make the eye appear smaller. Brown liner often looks softer and more natural on hooded eyes than stark black, especially for daytime wear. For the lower lash line, a smudged pencil in a medium brown adds depth without closing off the eye.",
    },
    {
      q: "What is the best mascara for hooded eyes?",
      a: "The best mascara for hooded eyes is usually a lightweight, smudge-resistant lengthening formula with a brush that can reach the outer lashes. Heavy volumizing formulas can transfer onto the hood, especially if your lashes touch the upper fold. Curl first, apply thin coats, and concentrate the most length on the outer third for lift.",
    },
    {
      q: "Can I do a cut crease with hooded eyes?",
      a: "A traditional cut crease can be challenging on hooded eyes because the fold hides the sharp line you create. However, an adapted 'open-eye cut crease' technique works beautifully: apply your concealer base with your eyes looking straight ahead, placing the cut line where you want the shadow to be visible. This means the actual crease line will sit slightly above your natural fold. Use a long-wearing concealer and set with translucent powder before adding shimmer on the lid. The key is designing the look for how your eyes appear when open, not closed.",
    },
  ],
};

const relatedLinks = [
  { label: "AI Makeup Try-On", url: "/ai-makeup-try-on" },
  { label: "Virtual Makeup App", url: "/virtual-makeup-app" },
  {
    label: "Personalized Recommendations",
    url: "/personalized-makeup-recommendation",
  },
  { label: "Makeup for Beginners", url: "/guides/beginner-tutorial" },
];
---

<SeoLandingLayout
  title={page.title}
  description={page.description}
  faq={page.faq}
>
  <div slot="hero">
    <h1>{page.title}</h1>
    <p>
      Hooded eyes aren't a problem to fix; they're an eye shape that requires
      different techniques. This guide covers everything from understanding the
      anatomy to practical application methods that keep your makeup visible.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="seo-content">
    <h2>Understanding Hooded Eyes: More Than Just a "Heavy Lid"</h2>

    <p>
      Hooded eyes are one of the most common eye shapes, yet they receive the
      least tailored advice in mainstream beauty content. The defining
      characteristic is a skin fold that drapes from the brow bone downward,
      partially or completely concealing the mobile eyelid. This is different
      from deep-set eyes, which are positioned further back in the orbital bone,
      and different from prominent or protruding eyes, which bulge forward.
    </p>

    <p>
      Many people don't realize they have hooded eyes because the condition can
      be asymmetrical, age-related, or subtle. Someone might have one hooded eye
      and one with a visible crease. Others develop hooding gradually as skin
      elasticity changes. The degree of hooding matters enormously for technique
      selection: a light hood requires only minor placement adjustments, while a
      heavy hood demands a complete redesign of your eye makeup strategy.
    </p>

    <p>
      The core challenge with hooded eyes is what we call the "crease illusion."
      When you apply eyeshadow in your natural crease (the fold you see when
      your eyes are open), most of that color disappears behind the hood. This
      is why so many tutorials feel like they're describing a different face.
      The techniques below are designed for how hooded eyes actually behave, not
      for a generic eye shape.
    </p>

    <h2>The Crease Illusion Technique: Working with What You See</h2>

    <p>
      The crease illusion technique involves creating a false crease line that
      sits above your natural fold. The principle is simple but
      counterintuitive: you apply transition and depth shades higher than where
      your actual crease sits, so that when your eyes are open (the position
      other people see you in), the gradient of color creates the appearance of
      dimension and structure.
    </p>

    <p>
      Start by looking straight into a mirror and identifying the highest point
      of your hood. This is your working canvas. Everything below this line
      risks being hidden. Your "new crease" should be positioned about two to
      three millimeters above this point, blending upward toward the brow bone.
      Use a fluffy blending brush with a matte transition shade that's one to
      two tones darker than your skin. Build the color gradually in
      windshield-wiper motions, focusing on the outer two-thirds of the eye.
    </p>

    <p>
      The result is not a dramatic transformation but a subtle optical effect.
      When done correctly, the viewer's eye perceives depth and structure where
      the hood would otherwise flatten the appearance. This technique forms the
      foundation for every other hooded-eye makeup application.
    </p>

    <h3>Why Regular Eyeshadow Tutorials Fail Hooded Eyes</h3>

    <p>
      Standard tutorials assume the crease is a visible landmark. They instruct
      you to "pack color into the crease" and "blend into the outer V." For
      someone with visible lid space, this works perfectly. For hooded eyes,
      these instructions deposit color precisely where it will be swallowed by
      skin contact.
    </p>

    <p>
      The second failure point is shimmer placement. Many tutorials put shimmer
      on the center of the lid for a pop of light. On hooded eyes, this shimmer
      gets squished into the fold, where it can actually emphasize puffiness
      rather than adding dimension. Instead, place shimmer on the inner corner
      and the brow bone, keeping the mobile lid area matte or satin.
    </p>

    <h2>Step-by-Step: Hooded Eyes Eyeshadow Routine</h2>

    <div class="step-list">
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Prime with a Thin, Matte Base</h4>
          <p>
            Apply a thin layer of eyeshadow primer using your ring finger,
            pressing it into the lid and up to the brow bone. Avoid thick primer
            formulas, which add bulk and accelerate creasing on hooded skin.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Set with Translucent Powder</h4>
          <p>
            Lightly dust translucent powder over the primed area. This creates a
            smooth, even surface that helps shadow blend more easily and
            prevents the tacky primer from grabbing pigment too aggressively.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Map the False Crease</h4>
          <p>
            Looking straight ahead, identify where you want the visible depth to
            appear. Apply a matte transition shade slightly above your natural
            fold, blending upward in gentle back-and-forth motions. This is the
            most critical step for hooded eyes.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Add Outer V Depth</h4>
          <p>
            Using a smaller, more precise brush, concentrate a deeper matte
            shade on the outer corner, extending it slightly upward along the
            false crease line. This elongates the eye and draws attention away
            from the hood itself.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Apply Lid Color Strategically</h4>
          <p>
            Place a light-to-medium shade on the visible portion of the mobile
            lid, staying below the false crease. Keep shimmer to the inner
            corner and brow bone only; use matte or satin finishes on the main
            lid area.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Tight-Line and Define Lashes</h4>
          <p>
            Apply a thin line of brown or black liner along the upper lash line,
            keeping it tight to the lashes. Focus on the outer half and create a
            subtle upward flick. Curl lashes and apply mascara, concentrating on
            the outer corners for a lifting effect.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Do This, Not That: Hooded Eye Guidelines</h2>

    <div class="feature-grid">
      <div class="feature-card">
        <div class="icon">DO</div>
        <h4>Look Straight Ahead</h4>
        <p>
          Apply and check your makeup with eyes open and looking forward. This
          is how the world sees you.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <div class="icon">AVOID</div>
        <h4>Heavy Shimmer on the Lid</h4>
        <p>
          Shimmer folds into the hood, creating a metallic stripe instead of a
          luminous lid.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <div class="icon">DO</div>
        <h4>Extend Wing Upward</h4>
        <p>
          An upward-flicking eyeliner wing creates lift and draws the eye above
          the hood line.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <div class="icon">AVOID</div>
        <h4>Thick Upper Liner</h4>
        <p>
          Thick lines get swallowed by the hood and transfer to the upper fold,
          creating a messy look.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <div class="icon">DO</div>
        <h4>Use Matte Transition Shades</h4>
        <p>
          Matte shades build dimension without reflecting light into the fold
          area where it emphasizes texture.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <div class="icon">AVOID</div>
        <h4>Dark Lower Lash Lines</h4>
        <p>
          Heavy lower lash liner closes off the eye, which is counterproductive
          when the upper lid is already partially hidden.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p>
        <strong>Common Mistake:</strong> The number one error people with hooded eyes
        make is applying eyeshadow while looking down into a mirror. This opens the
        lid fully and hides the hood, making it impossible to see where the color
        will actually land. Always check your work with eyes open and looking straight
        ahead. If you can't see the eyeshadow when your eyes are open, it needs to
        be placed higher.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>Lash and Brow Tips for Hooded Eyes</h2>

    <p>
      Lashes play an outsized role in hooded-eye makeup because they are one of
      the few elements that remain fully visible. Curling your lashes before
      applying mascara creates an upward sweep that counteracts the downward
      pull of the hood. Focus mascara application on the outer lashes and
      consider a slightly longer formula on the outer corner to enhance the
      lifting effect.
    </p>

    <p>
      If you are comparing the best mascara for hooded eyes, start with transfer
      control rather than maximum volume. A lighter lengthening formula keeps
      the lash line visible without stamping the upper fold, and a curved or
      tapered wand helps you build lift on the outer third of the eye.
    </p>

    <p>
      Your brows also frame hooded eyes differently than other eye shapes.
      Well-groomed, slightly arched brows create the impression of more lid
      space by drawing the eye upward. Avoid overly flat brow shapes, which
      reinforce the horizontal weight of the hood. A gentle arch that peaks just
      past the outer iris helps balance the overall composition.
    </p>

    <h2>Testing Your Look Before You Leave</h2>

    <p>
      The final test for any hooded-eye makeup look: sit in natural lighting,
      look straight into a mirror at eye level, and assess what you can actually
      see. If your eyeshadow creates a pleasant gradient of depth, your liner
      adds subtle definition without heaviness, and your lashes frame the eye
      without being overwhelmed, you have a look that works. If the shadow
      disappears or the liner looks like a dark smudge, the placement needs
      adjustment. The beauty of mastering these techniques is that once you
      understand the geometry of your own eyes, you can adapt any trend to work
      with your shape rather than against it.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div slot="cta">
    <div class="seo-cta">
      <div class="seo-cta-inner">
        <h2>See How Eye Makeup Looks on You</h2>
        <p>
          Try our AI-powered makeup try-on to test eyeshadow placements,
          eyeliner styles, and lash looks tailored to your eye shape before
          committing to real products.
        </p>
        <a href="/tryon" class="cta-btn">Try It Free</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div slot="related">
    <section class="seo-related">
      <div class="related-inner">
        <h3>Explore More</h3>
        <ul class="related-list">
          {
            relatedLinks.map((link) => (
              <li>
                <a href={link.url}>{link.label}</a>
              </li>
            ))
          }
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</SeoLandingLayout>
